         <entryFree xml:id="k000278" type="architectural feature">
            <term xml:id="term-k000278-1" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin-nt">chuiji</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000278-2" xml:lang="zh-Hant">垂脊</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000278-3" xml:lang="zh-Hans">垂脊</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000278-4" xml:lang="zh-latn-pinyin">chuíjǐ</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000278-5" xml:lang="zh-latn-wadegile">ch`ui-chi</term>
            <term xml:id="term-k000278-6" xml:lang="en" source="#biblk000278-1" type="literal_translation">descending ridge (lit.)</term>
            <idno type="URI">https://architecturasinica.org/keyword/k000278</idno>
            <note type="Note">
               <p>under construction</p>
               <p xml:lan="en">Literally “descending‘spine,” chuiji 垂脊 refers to a type of roof ridge. The term was first documented in the <term ref="/keyword/k000055">Northern Song</term> dynasty (960-1127) and its meaning has 
                  evolved over time. From the Song dynasty “Linchuan xiansheng wenji” (Collected Writings of Wang Anshi (1021-1086), and Yingzao fashi, to the Qing dynasty “Wenxian juli,” chuiji 
                  primarily referred to the ridges that run perpendicular to the main ridge on both roof faces. It was commonly used in buildings with hip-gable (<term ref="/keyword/k000143">xieshan 歇山</term>) and 
                  gabled (<term ref="/keyword/k000146">xuanshan 懸山</term>) roofs. （Wang 2023, 863; Li 2009, 6.10a; Ru et al. 2000, 4-143; Anonymous 2000, 4-362） During the <term ref="/keyword/k000051">Ming</term> and <term ref="/keyword/k000070">Qing</term> dynasties (1368-1911), the term chuiji could 
                  also be used to refer to the chuiji tongzi 垂脊筒子, which are the brick or glazed tile pieces used to construct these descending ridges.（He 2013, 131; Anonymous 2000, 295）Modern 
                  scholars have broadened the meaning of chuiji to include ridges intersecting with the main ridge in hipped roof (<term ref="/keyword/k000125">wudian 廡殿</term>) structures and ridges connecting to the jewel-shaped 
                  finial (baoding 寶頂) of pointed roof (<term ref="/keyword/k000188">cuanjian 攢尖</term>) buildings. （Liang 1981, 80; Liang and Liu 1935, 4; Liu 1993, 166）</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">“垂脊”指中國古代建築中屋脊的一種。垂脊一词最早出现于北宋文献，自宋至今其所指有扩展。</p>
               <p xml:lang="zh-Hant">由宋《臨川先生文集》（王 2023,863）;《營造法式》（李 2009,6.10a））至清（如《帝阙城垣规制》茹敦和 等  2000,4-141、4-143）;《地宫作法》佚名 2000,4-362）， “垂脊”主要指與正脊垂直、
                  位於屋坡兩側邊緣的屋脊，用於歇山頂和兩坡頂。明清时期，“垂脊”一詞還可指代“垂脊筒子”，即一種安裝於垂脊位置的磚件或琉璃件。（如《工部廠庫須知》何 2013,131；《內庭工程做法則例》佚名 2000,295）現代學者將垂脊擴展
                  至指廡殿頂與攢尖頂中與正脊或寶頂相交之脊（梁 1981,80；梁和刘 1935,4；刘 1993,166 。</p>                
            </note>
